{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17624"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17624"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71672"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10338"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57168"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7754"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24186"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71672"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is designing a clinical trial to test whether a new analgesic medication reduces post-operative pain more effectively than placebo. They want to ensure their study has adequate statistical power.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a type II error in this context?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Correctly identifying that the analgesic is not effective","Failing to detect a true difference between analgesic and placebo","Correctly identifying that the analgesic is effective","Incorrectly rejecting the null hypothesis","Incorrectly concluding the analgesic is effective when it is not"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etype II error occurs when failing to detect a true difference between analgesic and placebo\u003C/strong\u003E. This represents failing to reject a false null hypothesis (beta error). In this case, concluding there is no effect when the medication actually is effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncorrectly concluding the analgesic is effective when it is not \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eincorrectly rejecting the null hypothesis\u003C/strong\u003E - These both describe a type I error (alpha), not a type II error\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorrectly identifying that the analgesic is not effective\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a correct acceptance of the null hypothesis, not an error\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorrectly identifying that the analgesic is effective\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents statistical power (1-beta), the opposite of a type II error\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStatistical power (1-beta) is the probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis. Increasing sample size and effect size will increase power and reduce the probability of type II errors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type II error (beta) occurs when failing to reject a false null hypothesis - a false negative","Statistical power (1-beta) is the probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis","Increasing sample size reduces the probability of type II errors and increases statistical power"],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57168"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17624"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57168"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T10:49:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T10:52:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10338"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71672"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-